\section{Introduction}

Satellite detections of hail signatures are subject to uncertainty in the
tropics, where there are marked differences in reported climatologies. The deep
troposphere can allow for detection of ice aloft that may melt before reaching
the surface. While it is often assumed that surface hail in the tropics is
overestimated by satellite remote-sensing platforms, a lack of ground hail
observations in many tropical regions means that the extent to which ice aloft
melts before reaching the surface has not been investigated in detail. Here, we
examine  numerical weather simulations of locations and times with satellite
detections of hail over Australia's tropics, to determine the conditions under
which surface hail occurrence is plausible.

Global hail climatologies based on satellite retrievals differ in their
estimations of hail occurrence in the tropics, with some estimating that the
tropical landmasses within about 15$^{\circ}$ of the equator experience
relatively high hail occurrence aloft, especially across Africa
\citep{Ferraro_AR_2015, Mroz_JAMC_2017, Ni_JAMC_2017}, while
\cite{Cecil_JC_2012} explicitly artificially scaled their results to account for
expected overestimation in the tropics. The climatology of \cite{Bang_JAMC_2019}
used tropopause height to normalise brightness temperature depression to account
for increased storm depth in tropical regions, which reduced hail probabilities
in the tropics.

Hail proxies, which statistically link large-scale atmospheric environments to
hail occurrence, are also subject to high uncertainty in tropical regions. For
example, \cite{Raupach_MWR_2023} showed that common instability- and shear-based
hail proxies overestimate hail probability in Australia's tropical regions, and
proposed an improved proxy that exploits latitudinal variation in hail-prone
conditions and additional threshold-based constraints that further reduced the
false alarm rate. \cite{Brook_MWR_2024}'s radar-based climatology for hail in
Australia noted very little hail activity at two radar sites at $\sim$18
S$^{\circ}$ and $\sim$17$^{\circ}$, lending weight to the theory that while deep
convection based on high instability, often including overshooting tops
\cite{Bedka_JAMC_2018},  occurs frequently in the tropics, satellite- and
proxy-based hail climatologies that do not explicitly account for deeper storms
and increased melting in the tropics may overestimate hail occurrences in these
regions. 



\todo{Frisby and Sansom (1967) first reviewed hail occurrence in tropical
