\section{Data and Methods}

\subsection{Hailstorm detections}

Hail signatures were those detected using the algorithm of \cite{Bang_JAMC_2019}
applied to passive microwave measurements of the Global Precipitation
Measurement \citep[GPM,][]{Hou_BAMS_2014} Microwave Imager. The detections for
this study we the detections to those with probability over 0.5, not flagged for
snow or surface feature inclusion, between January 2014 and September 2023, in
the region between 115 $^{\circ}$E to 146 $^{\circ}$E longitude and 10
$^{\circ}$S to 20 $^{\circ}$S latitude. There were
\Sexpr{results[['number_detections']]} such satellite-based hail detections.

\subsection{Downscaled simulations}

We used the Advanced Research Weather and Forecasting model
\citep[AR-WRF,][]{Skamarock_2021} v4.6.0 to simulate the hours around each
satellite hailstorm detection. For each simulation, we ran WRF for a period of
15 hours of simulation time, comprising 12 hours of model spin-up which was not
considered in the analyses, the hour before the hail detection, the hour of the
detection, and the hour afterwards. Boundary conditions were provided by
European Centre for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts Reanalysis 5
\citep[ERA5,][]{Hersbach_QJRMS_2020} data. The models were run with three nested
domains of 120 $\times$ 120 mass points each, centred on the satellite hail
detection; with outer to inner domain grid spacings of 9 km, 3 km, and 1 km. 79
vertical mass points were used with a model-top pressure of 50 hPa. The model
timestep was 18 seconds and output was written at 5 minute intervals. The domain
with 9 km grid spacing had the New Tiedtke \citep{Zhang_JC_2017} cumulus scheme
enabled, while no cumulus parameterisation was used in the finer-resolution
domains. Across all domains, we used the RRTMG radiation scheme
\citep{Iacono_JGRA_2008}, the revised MM5 Monin-Obukhov surface layer scheme
\citep{Jimenez_MWR_2012}, the YSU planetary boundary layer scheme
\citep{Hong_MWR_2006}, and the Noah-MP land-surface scheme
\citep{Niu_JGRA_2011}. WRF-HAILCAST \citep{Adams-Selin_WF_2019} was enabled on
the 3 km and 1 km domains to estimate surface hailstone sizes. For each
hailstorm detection we ran four model instances only differing in the choice of
microphysics scheme. The four parameterisations considered were the NSSL
2-moment with cloud condensation nuclei prediction
\citep[][]{Mansell_JAS_2010}, Thompson 2-moment \citep{Thompson_MWR_2008}, P3
3-moment \citep[][]{Milbrandt_JAS_2021}, and MY2 \citep{Milbrandt_JAS_2005a,
Milbrandt_JAS_2005b} schemes.

\subsection{Data processing}

Variables on a variable vertical grid were interpolated to a regular grid with
levels from 1000 hPa to 100 hPa with 50 hPa increments, without extrapolation
outside the model vertical pressure range. Derived variables were calculated
using WRF-Python version 1.3.4.1 \citep{wrf-python}, MetPy version 1.7.0
\citep{metpy}, and xarray\_parcel version 1.0.8 \citep{Raupach_xarray_zenodo}.
Simulation results were subset to the 12 five-minute time steps covering the
hour of the corresponding satellite detection. We considered a simulation to
include hail if HAILCAST produced surface hail of at least
\Sexpr{results['hail_threshold']} during the hour of detection -- this threshold
was chosen to focus on damaging hail, which is normally considered to be 2 cm or
larger, as well as to align with the data used to train the satellite-detection
algorithm of \cite{Bang_JAMC_2019} which contained hail over 18 (before 2010) or
over 25 mm (after 2010).

\section{Results}

\begin{figure}[bt]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/sims_map}
    \caption{Simulation locations. Each location corresponds to a satellite
    detection for which four simulations were produced. Markers representing the
    microphysics (MP) scheme and whether the simulation produced surface hail
    surround each detection location. The x and y axes show longitude and
    latitude, respectively, and the globe shows the study location (shaded red)
    in context.}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Production of surface hail}

Of the \Sexpr{results[['number_detections']]*4} cases analysed,
\Sexpr{results[['hail_cases']]}
(\Sexpr{round(results[['hail_cases']]/(results[['number_detections']]*4)*100,
0)}\%) produced surface hail, while the remaining
\Sexpr{results[['nohail_cases']]} did not.

\subsection{Skew-T analyses}

Figure \ref{fig:skewTs} shows mean pseudo-soundings across all events, by
microphysics scheme and categorised by whether the simulation produced surface
hail. The mean profiles all showed significant instability with deep regions of
positive buoyancy for a parcel lifted from 1000 hPa, and thus high values of
convective available potential energy. Convective inhibition was present below
$\sim$750 hPa, with slightly more inhibition present in cases with surface hail
than those without for the MY2, NSSL, and Thompson microphysics schemes. The
most notable difference between hail and no-hail cases was that the hail cases
contained more moisture above $\sim$500 hPa, although we note there was overlap
in the dewpoint distributions.

\begin{figure}[bt]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{figures/skewT_comp}
    \caption{Log p skew T plots showing mean profiles for all simulations that
    produced surface hail (H, pink) and those that did not produce surface hail
    (NH, green). Black lines show the lifted temperature profiles for the mean
    1000 hPa parcel across all simulations.}
    \label{fig:skewTs}
\end{figure}

